column2: The Politically Incorrect Guide to American History
column27: Claiming that most textbooks and popular history books were written by biased left-wing writers and scholars, historian Thomas Woods offers this guide as an alternative to \the stale and predictable platitudes of mainstream texts.\" Covering the colonial era through the Clinton administration
column28: Woods seeks to debunk some persistent myths about American history. For instance
column30: the Puritans were not racists intent on stealing the Indians’ lands
column31: the Founding Fathers were not revolutionaries but conservatives in the true sense of the word
column32: the American War Between the States (to even call it a civil war is inaccurate
column33: Woods says) was not principally about slavery
column34: Abraham Lincoln was no friend to the slaves
column35: and FDR’s New Deal policies actually made the Depression worse. He also covers a wide range of constitutional interpretations over the years
column40: and continually makes the point that states’ rights have been unlawfully trampled upon by the federal government since the early days of the republic. Though its title is more deliberately provocative than accurate
column41: Woods’ attack on what he sees as rampant liberal revisionism over the past 25 years proves to be an interesting platform for a book. He’s as biased as those he rails against
column43: but he does provoke thought in an entertaining way even if he sometimes tries to pass off opinion as hard facts.This quick and enjoyable read is packed with unfamiliar quotes
column46: and a list of books \"you’re not supposed to read.\" It is not a comprehensive or detailed study
column47: but that is not its aim; instead
